  "id": "019d37f9-ad5f-7360-b385-d2036f82fea3",
  "content": "# Agent Teams Phase 4: LLM Extraction and Scope Promotion -- Decision Record (2026-03-29)\n## What: Added optional LLM extraction pass that identifies decisions, findings, and questions in team message entries and promotes product-relevant ones to the corvia scope.\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Two-component architecture: Adapter writes source_versions to .classify-queue (per-team, crash-safe), server handles LLM extraction and promotion via POST /v1/classify/agent-teams. Adapter stays simple (no HTTP/gRPC deps), server has access to GenerationEngine and GraphStore.\n2. Two-stage LLM pipeline: First call extracts structured items (JSON array of decision/finding/question), second call classifies each for product relevance (YES/NO). Extraction always persists to user-history scope regardless of promotion outcome, preserving full provenance.\n3. Source_version uses parent entry_ref as prefix (e.g. team:messages:task-1:extracted:1) to avoid cross-batch collisions. The global counter approach was flagged by all 5 reviewers during the review phase.\n4. Embedding reuse for promoted entries: promoted copy reuses the extracted entry's embedding vector instead of re-computing it (content is identical). Saves one inference call per promotion.\n5. Response separates rejected (entry not found) from skipped (nothing to extract) from failed (transient errors) for clear operational metrics.\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- MockGenerationEngine returns the same response for all calls. To test both extraction AND promotion, use a response that starts with \"YES\" and contains valid JSON (e.g. \"YES. [{...}]\") so the parser finds the array and the promotion classifier sees \"YES\".\n- Per-team .classify-queue writes match the crash-safety pattern established for .ingested in Phase 2. Batching queue writes to end-of-run was flagged as a regression from that pattern.\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Nothing blocked. RFC Section 7 was well-specified.\n- The sv_lookup HashMap borrows from uh_entries, so the cloned entry was unnecessary. Using a reference avoids copying the embedding vector (~3KB per entry).",
